<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,151,680]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,151,176]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<collectingRegion box="[332,352,152,176]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">A</collectingRegion>
mylabrine genus similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marseul" authorityYear="1872" box="[690,810,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mimesthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[690,810,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Mimesthes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis, 2018" authorityName="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis" authorityYear="2018" box="[874,1047,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Paramimesthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n">
<emphasis box="[874,1047,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Paramimesthes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1067,1159,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1844,1866]" captionTargetBox="[200,1403,233,1794]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[168,1453,193,1830]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 2. A. Prionotolytta binotata; B. Prionotolytta eremita; C. Prionotolytta hayekae; D. Prionotolytta melanura; E. Prionotolytta streyi; F. Prolytta coriacea; G. Prolytta namibensis; H. Prolytta pseudolucida; I. Cyaneolytta affinis; J. Cyaneolytta depressicornis; K. Cyaneolytta granulipennis; L. Cyaneolytta maculifrons; M. Cyaneolytta resplendens; N. Epicauta designata; O. Epicauta ovampoa; P. Epicauta rufifrons; Q. Epicauta velata; R. Psalydolytta gessi; S. Psalydolytta lorigera; T. Actenodia chrysomelina; U. Actenodia mirabilis; V. Mimesthes maculicollis; W. Mimesthes nigricollis; X. Paramimesthes namibicus; Y. Namylabris adamantifera." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151730/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 2Y</figureCitation>
), but with some mixed characters of other mylabrine genera, distinct by the combination of the following characters: temples elongate and parallel, mandible elongate, greatly longer than labrum, sharped; antennae slender, progressively and sligthly widened apically, neither subclavate nor VIII–XI so approached to form a club, but only progressively widened apically, antennomeres III–XI red or dark brown; pronotum not distinctly transverse, only few wider than maximal width of head, subcampaniform; mesosternum without modified fore portion, mesepisternum without furrowed border; male protarsomeres not widened internally; male claw ventrally regularly curved, not angulate; male margin of penultimate ventrite widely emarginated and depressed; aedeagus similar tho that of the genus 
<emphasis box="[151,277,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marseul" authorityYear="1872" box="[151,274,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mimesthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mimesthes</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
apically not incised with both hooks very far from apex, the proximal one smooth and short.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="45" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,151,680]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,476,501]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Description</emphasis>
. Head elongate, parallel, temples parallel, particularly in female, about as long as longitudinal diameter of eye; frons dorsally flat, about twice as wide as transverse diameter of eye; eyes only slightly convex. Clypeus about as long as labrum, which is slightly emarginated anteriorly. Galeae, maxillary and labial palpi not modified; mandibles elongate and sharp. Eleven antennomeres (
<figureCitation box="[884,990,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1641,1663]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,743,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[151,1436,733,1620]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 10. Namylabris adamantifera: tegmen in ventral (A), dorsal (B) and lateral view (C); aedeagus in lateral view (D); pronotum (E); mesostsernum (F); antenna (G). Bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151760/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 10G</figureCitation>
), VI–X progressively few widened but not forming club, III–VII subcylindrical, X–XI only slightly wider than VIII–IX, XI slightly narrower than X; basal six with distinctly longer setae, remaining with a very short and dense clear microsetation.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151760/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" targetBox="[161,1424,743,1601]" targetPageId="44">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1435,1641,1694]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,1641,1663]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">FIGURE 10.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis" authorityYear="2018" box="[296,558,1641,1663]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Namylabris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adamantifera">
<emphasis box="[296,558,1641,1663]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Namylabris adamantifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: tegmen in ventral (A), dorsal (B) and lateral view (C); aedeagus in lateral view (D); pronotum (E); mesostsernum (F); antenna (G). Bar = 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,1733,2010]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[327,428,1733,1758]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1641,1663]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,743,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[151,1436,733,1620]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 10. Namylabris adamantifera: tegmen in ventral (A), dorsal (B) and lateral view (C); aedeagus in lateral view (D); pronotum (E); mesostsernum (F); antenna (G). Bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151760/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 10E</figureCitation>
) only slightly wider than long, subcampaniform, subparallel in basal half, progressively narrowed after middle; rebordered at base, with a basal depression in middle and three subrounded depressions just before middle. Mesosternum (
<figureCitation box="[507,610,1805,1830]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1641,1663]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,743,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[151,1436,733,1620]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 10. Namylabris adamantifera: tegmen in ventral (A), dorsal (B) and lateral view (C); aedeagus in lateral view (D); pronotum (E); mesostsernum (F); antenna (G). Bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151760/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 10F</figureCitation>
) without clearly modified fore area, but only with a shagreened and umpunctate triangular fore part; mesepisterna smooth, anterior edge lacking furrowed border. Elytra subplanate and subsquared at apex. Male protarsomeres slender; female protibia and protarsomeres with robust distinct setae; female protibia not distinctly elongate or pointed on external apex; pro-mesotarsomeres with small ventral pad; male claws ventrally progressively curved in both sexes. Pro-mesotibial spurs elongate and pointed; metatibial spurs both narrow and stick-like.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Male penultimate ventrite widely emarginated and depressed posteriorly in middle, where is present an unpunctate and unsetate shiny area; last ventrite triangularly emarginated. Male gonostyli ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[1278,1380,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1641,1663]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,743,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[151,1436,733,1620]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 10. Namylabris adamantifera: tegmen in ventral (A), dorsal (B) and lateral view (C); aedeagus in lateral view (D); pronotum (E); mesostsernum (F); antenna (G). Bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151760/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 10 
<collectingRegion box="[1358,1380,188,212]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
</figureCitation>
) and dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[260,363,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1641,1663]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,743,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[151,1436,733,1620]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 10. Namylabris adamantifera: tegmen in ventral (A), dorsal (B) and lateral view (C); aedeagus in lateral view (D); pronotum (E); mesostsernum (F); antenna (G). Bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151760/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
) subcylindrical and slender, apically narrowed; laterally (
<figureCitation box="[1034,1138,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1641,1663]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,743,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[151,1436,733,1620]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 10. Namylabris adamantifera: tegmen in ventral (A), dorsal (B) and lateral view (C); aedeagus in lateral view (D); pronotum (E); mesostsernum (F); antenna (G). Bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151760/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
) slender and narrowed at apex; gonocoxal piece suboval in ventral view; aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[810,913,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1641,1663]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,743,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[151,1436,733,1620]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 10. Namylabris adamantifera: tegmen in ventral (A), dorsal (B) and lateral view (C); aedeagus in lateral view (D); pronotum (E); mesostsernum (F); antenna (G). Bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151760/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 10D</figureCitation>
) apically with a short incision, at apex curved posteriad, with distal hook extremely far from apex, pointed and curved, and a small residual proximal hook, smooth at apex similar than in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marseul" authorityYear="1872" box="[610,730,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mimesthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[610,730,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Mimesthes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; endophallic hook very small and not easily visible.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,367,392]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name refers to the Namaqualand desert, where the genus is distributed (in both 
<collectingRegion box="[1271,1436,367,392]" country="South Africa" name="Northern Cape" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[1271,1372,367,392]" country="Zambia" name="Northern" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Northern</collectingRegion>
Cape
</collectingRegion>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[198,297,404,429]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aizoaceae" genus="Namibia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="45" pageNumber="129" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<collectingCountry box="[198,297,404,429]" name="Namibia" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Namibia</collectingCountry>
</taxonomicName>
) and to its general similarity with the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[795,896,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mylabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[795,896,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Mylabris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Feminine genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
